    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nHi, since https://github.com/neovim/neovim/pull/39176 the behavior of `vim.fn.environ()` changed on Windows, with keys no longer being uppercased. This was originally implemented in https://github.com/neovim/neovim/pull/14579 (issue https://github.com/neovim/neovim/issues/14541). I'm not sure if this is still an issue within Neovim on Windows but it did cause some breakage in user code. I'm accessing the `PATH` variable via `vim.fn.environ()`, something that up until #39176 worked fine on all platforms.\n\nFigured I'd raise an issue in case this might cause regressions internally but also inform that it might break user code and probably deserves being highlighted in the next release changelog.\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\nOn a Windows machine:\n\n```vim\n\" On latest stable (0.12.2) this returns environment variables with all keys UPPERCASED\n\" On nightly/master this returns environment variables as-is\n:=vim.fn.environ()\n```\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nFor `vim.fn.environ()` to return keys uppercased, consistent with previous behavior.\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\nNVIM v0.13.0-dev-347+g689c824ef7\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nno, 9.2.0323. Vim does return some environments \"as-is\", but `PATH` gets uppercased.\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nWindows 11\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nWindows Terminal\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nN/A\n\n### Installation\n\nOfficial release assets",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
